Cloud computing is a model for delivering computing services such as servers, storage, databases, networking, software, and analytics over the internet. Instead of owning physical hardware, users can access resources on demand from cloud providers. This model provides scalability, flexibility, and cost efficiency.

There are three main types of cloud service models. Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) provides virtualized computing resources over the internet, allowing users to rent virtual machines and storage. Platform as a Service (PaaS) offers a platform that allows developers to build, test, and deploy applications without managing underlying infrastructure. Software as a Service (SaaS) delivers software applications over the internet on a subscription basis.

Cloud deployment models include public cloud, private cloud, and hybrid cloud. Public clouds are operated by third-party providers and shared among multiple users. Private clouds are dedicated to a single organization, offering greater control and security. Hybrid clouds combine both public and private environments to optimize performance and cost.

Despite its advantages, cloud computing also presents challenges. Security and data privacy remain major concerns, especially when sensitive data is stored on third-party servers. Downtime and service outages can impact business operations. Additionally, vendor lock-in can make it difficult to switch providers.

To maximize the benefits of cloud computing, organizations must adopt proper security measures, ensure compliance with regulations, and design resilient architectures. As technology evolves, cloud computing continues to play a vital role in digital transformation.